As several San Francisco Bay area issued lockdown orders on Monday to try and halt the spread of the coronavirus, electric-car maker Tesla Inc. TSLA, +4.27% will reportedly keep its Fremont electric vehicle assembly plant open. The company has been declared an "essential business" and can remain operating, said a county spokesman, according to a report in the LA Times. A spokesperson for Tesla could not immediately be reached for comment. Tesla Chief Executive Elon Musk reportedly emailed employees late Monday, telling them they should not feel "obligated" to come to work if they do not feel 100% or even aren't comfortable with the idea. Despite market volatility due to the virus outbreak, Tesla shares are up 6% year to date, against a 26% plunge for the S&P 500 SPX, +0.26%.